</p><p>This has a simple probabilistic interpretation. Consider a random walk on the integer line, starting at 0. Let −1 be a "trap" state, such that if the walker arrives at −1, it will remain there. The walker can arrive at the trap state at times <span class="nowrap">1, 3, 5, 7,…</span> and the number of ways the walker can arrive at the trap state at time <span class="texhtml">2<i>k</i> + 1</span> is <span class="texhtml"><i>C</i><sub><i>k</i></sub></span>. Since the one-dimensional random walk is recurrent, the probability that the walker eventually arrives at −1 is
