solves the combinatorial problems listed above. The first proof below uses a <a href="/wiki/Generating_function" title="Generating function">generating function</a>. The other proofs are examples of <a href="/wiki/Bijective_proof" title="Bijective proof">bijective proofs</a>; they involve literally counting a collection of some kind of object to arrive at the correct formula.
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id="First_proof">First proof</h3><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Catalan_number&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: First proof"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>We first observe that all of the combinatorial problems listed above satisfy <a href="/wiki/Johann_Andreas_Segner" title="Johann Andreas Segner">Segner's</a><sup id="cite&#95;ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>9<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Recurrence_relation" title="Recurrence relation">recurrence relation</a>
</p><p><span class="mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"  alttext="{\displaystyle C_{0}=1\quad {\text{and}}\quad C_{n+1}=\sum _{i=0}^{n}C_{i}\,C_{n-i}\quad {\text{for }}n\geq 0\,.}">
