<div class="mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id="Fourth_proof">Fourth proof</h3><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Catalan_number&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Fourth proof"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>This proof uses the triangulation definition of Catalan numbers to establish a relation between <span class="texhtml"><i>C</i><sub><i>n</i></sub></span> and <span class="texhtml"><i>C</i><sub><i>n</i>+1</sub></span>.
</p><p>Given a polygon <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">P</span> with <span class="texhtml"><i>n</i> + 2</span> sides and a triangulation, mark one of its sides as the base, and also orient one of its <span class="texhtml">2<i>n</i> + 1</span> total edges. There are <span class="texhtml">(4<i>n</i> + 2)<i>C</i><sub><i>n</i></sub></span> such marked triangulations for a given base.
</p><p>Given a polygon <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">Q</span> with <span class="texhtml"><i>n</i> + 3</span> sides and a (different) triangulation, again mark one of its sides as the base. Mark one of the sides other than the base side (and not an inner triangle edge). There are <span class="texhtml">(<i>n</i> + 2)<i>C</i><sub><i>n</i> + 1</sub></span> such marked triangulations for a given base.
</p><p>There is a simple bijection between these two marked triangulations:  We can either collapse the triangle in <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">Q</span> whose side is marked (in two ways, and subtract the two that cannot collapse the base), or, in reverse, expand the oriented edge in <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">P</span> to a triangle and mark its new side.
